1
00:00:12,145 --> 00:00:15,114
[mysterious instrumental music]

2
00:02:18,338 --> 00:02:21,330
[police radio chatter]

3
00:02:32,285 --> 00:02:35,277
[crickets chirping]

4
00:02:50,537 --> 00:02:52,095
- Miss Deaver?

5
00:02:52,138 --> 00:02:54,504
It's Deputy Lura, Ma'am.

6
00:02:55,542 --> 00:02:57,203
Got a phone call from this house.

7
00:02:57,243 --> 00:02:58,733
Somebody hung up.

8
00:02:59,746 --> 00:03:02,806
Everything all right?

9
00:03:05,585 --> 00:03:07,576
Miss Deaver?

10
00:03:22,802 --> 00:03:25,566
Somebody in there?

11
00:03:28,608 --> 00:03:31,600
I can hear you, you know.

12
00:03:35,615 --> 00:03:40,075
Miss Deaver, is that you?

13
00:03:40,119 --> 00:03:43,111
[wind whistling]

14
00:03:50,997 --> 00:03:52,191
Jesus!

15
00:04:04,844 --> 00:04:08,780
- Mm-hmm.

16
00:04:08,815 --> 00:04:11,477
Okay.

17
00:04:11,517 --> 00:04:14,111
My aunt died.

18
00:04:14,153 --> 00:04:15,142
- Did she?

19
00:04:15,188 --> 00:04:16,212
- Yeah, they just found her.

20
00:04:16,256 --> 00:04:17,280
Looks like her heart.

21
00:04:17,323 --> 00:04:20,417
- Oh, God, that's awful.

22
00:04:20,460 --> 00:04:22,018
- Look at the bright side.

23
00:04:22,061 --> 00:04:23,756
We got the house.

24
00:04:23,796 --> 00:04:25,354
- What is the matter with you?

25
00:04:25,398 --> 00:04:26,524
- Oome on, Robin.

26
00:04:26,566 --> 00:04:28,864
Don't suddenly act like we were all close.

27
00:04:28,901 --> 00:04:30,459
That woman was cold as hell to us.

28
00:04:30,503 --> 00:04:31,492
- That's not the point.

29
00:04:31,537 --> 00:04:32,526
- What is the point, Robin?

30
00:04:32,572 --> 00:04:35,063
The point is, when someone just dies,
it's not a time to bad-mouth them.

31
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:37,269
It's a time to say a prayer
and count your own blessings.

32
00:04:40,179 --> 00:04:42,511
- I am countin' my blessings.

33
00:04:42,548 --> 00:04:44,175
I get the house.

34
00:04:44,217 --> 00:04:47,914
- Marlene Deaver was not a great Oatholic.

35
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:50,320
But she was a great bingo player.

36
00:04:50,356 --> 00:04:51,380
[laughter]

37
00:04:51,424 --> 00:04:54,393
But I'm guessing God will take her,
because where it counted,

38
00:04:54,427 --> 00:04:57,726
she loved her neighbor
with the best of them.

39
00:04:57,764 --> 00:04:59,026
- You've got to be kiddin' me.

40
00:04:59,065 --> 00:05:00,225
He doesn't show up
for his own aunt's funeral?

41
00:05:00,266 --> 00:05:02,734
- He's in mourning.
He's just probably runnin' a little late.

42
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:08,937
- He looks in a good mood.

43
00:05:08,975 --> 00:05:11,375
Someone should make sure he knows
that she didn't pull through.

44
00:05:11,411 --> 00:05:15,108
- He's very strong, Oarl.

45
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:16,206
- Hello, Oarl.

46
00:05:16,249 --> 00:05:17,739
- Sorry for your loss, Bryan.

47
00:05:17,784 --> 00:05:18,808
- What?

48
00:05:18,851 --> 00:05:20,819
Oh.
Oh, yeah.

49
00:05:20,853 --> 00:05:21,911
It's a sad day.

50
00:05:24,557 --> 00:05:25,683
So what'd I miss?

51
00:05:25,725 --> 00:05:28,091
- Her eternal soul
being lifted up into heaven.

52
00:05:28,127 --> 00:05:29,355
- Oh, shit.

53
00:05:29,395 --> 00:05:31,192
I really wanted to catch that.

54
00:05:31,230 --> 00:05:32,857
Hey, do you want to take a ride
with me later?

55
00:05:32,899 --> 00:05:33,923
I'll drop you back.
- Where?

56
00:05:33,966 --> 00:05:34,955
- My aunt's house.

57
00:05:35,001 --> 00:05:36,332
I just got the key
from the sheriff.

58
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:37,358
- Thank you.

59
00:05:37,403 --> 00:05:38,631
I may stop by.

60
00:05:41,574 --> 00:05:42,563
Bryan Becket.

61
00:05:42,608 --> 00:05:44,337
- Thank you for doing this, Father.

62
00:05:44,377 --> 00:05:45,537
She would've appreciated it.

63
00:05:45,578 --> 00:05:48,206
- Well, at least she came on time.

64
00:05:48,247 --> 00:05:50,374
You don't take any of this seriously,
do you?

65
00:05:50,416 --> 00:05:51,405
- What?

66
00:05:51,451 --> 00:05:53,282
- Religious ritual, the church.

67
00:05:53,319 --> 00:05:54,616
- Hey.

68
00:05:54,654 --> 00:05:56,178
I'd love to take the church seriously,

69
00:05:56,222 --> 00:05:58,383
but it's kind of hard
with the Pope runnin' around

70
00:05:58,424 --> 00:05:59,413
wearin' those hats.

71
00:05:59,459 --> 00:06:01,723
[laughter]

72
00:06:01,761 --> 00:06:03,922
- You want to know what I think
your problem with death is?

73
00:06:03,963 --> 00:06:04,952
- Not really.

74
00:06:04,997 --> 00:06:06,726
- You don't believe in anything, you know?

75
00:06:06,766 --> 00:06:07,824
You don't believe in a higher power.

76
00:06:07,867 --> 00:06:09,061
You don't believe
in the afterlife, nothin'.

77
00:06:09,102 --> 00:06:10,126
- You're right.

78
00:06:10,169 --> 00:06:12,228
Life would be easier if I were gullible.

79
00:06:12,271 --> 00:06:13,533
- You think I'm gullible, Becket?

80
00:06:13,573 --> 00:06:15,200
- Sully, you believe in everything.

81
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:16,230
- I don't believe in everything.

82
00:06:16,275 --> 00:06:17,264
- Yes, you do.
- No.

83
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:20,006
- Okay, didn't you once tell me
you believed in the Loch Ness monster?

84
00:06:20,046 --> 00:06:22,446
- They're gonna catch that sucker.

85
00:06:22,482 --> 00:06:23,540
You'll see.

86
00:06:23,583 --> 00:06:27,610
Scottish scientists went down
in that lake using sonar, Beck.

87
00:06:27,653 --> 00:06:29,245
- And their results were inconclusive.

88
00:06:29,288 --> 00:06:30,277
- Wrong!

89
00:06:30,323 --> 00:06:34,419
They picked up a large moving mass
changing directions in organic patterns.

90
00:06:34,460 --> 00:06:35,927
So what else could it be?

91
00:06:35,962 --> 00:06:36,951
- I don't know.

92
00:06:36,996 --> 00:06:39,157
I don't know what the military
was covering up at Roswell.

93
00:06:39,198 --> 00:06:40,460
Does that make it aliens?

94
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:42,627
- No, but alien bodies
on the ground made it aliens.

95
00:06:42,668 --> 00:06:44,101
- You know what your problem is, Sully?

96
00:06:44,137 --> 00:06:45,502
- What?
- You were raised Oatholic.

97
00:06:45,538 --> 00:06:46,527
- Oh, here we go.

98
00:06:46,572 --> 00:06:47,561
- Really, I mean it.

99
00:06:47,607 --> 00:06:49,768
How big a stretch can it be
believing in the Loch Ness monster

100
00:06:49,809 --> 00:06:51,208
once you bought the Holy Trinity?

101
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:55,977
There it is.
- Oh, my God.

102
00:06:56,015 --> 00:06:57,710
It's a monster.

103
00:06:57,750 --> 00:06:58,774
She lived there alone?

104
00:06:58,818 --> 00:07:00,080
I wouldn't be caught dead
alone in there.

105
00:07:00,119 --> 00:07:01,108
Oreep me out.

106
00:07:01,154 --> 00:07:03,054
- I can't wait to get in there.

107
00:07:03,089 --> 00:07:05,216
Hear there's all kinds of antiques,
even a wine cellar.

108
00:07:05,258 --> 00:07:06,384
- You hear?
Oh, that's right.

109
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:08,860
This is the aunt that didn't like you,
so she never invited you over.

110
00:07:08,895 --> 00:07:09,884
- I don't care if she didn't like me.

111
00:07:09,929 --> 00:07:10,918
She's dead now.

112
00:07:10,963 --> 00:07:12,692
I'm invitin' myself over.

113
00:07:12,732 --> 00:07:15,132
- Yeah, but why didn't she like you?

114
00:07:15,168 --> 00:07:16,396
- Don't know.

115
00:07:16,436 --> 00:07:19,564
- You know, I got to admit,
I find this all very, very intriguing.

116
00:07:19,605 --> 00:07:23,041
- Yeah, well you also find
astrology intriguing, and it's not.

117
00:07:27,413 --> 00:07:28,675
- [whistles]

118
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:30,648
Wow.

119
00:07:30,683 --> 00:07:32,014
How rich was she?

120
00:07:32,051 --> 00:07:33,348
- She wasn't rich.

121
00:07:33,386 --> 00:07:36,150
This house is the last
of the old family money.

122
00:07:36,189 --> 00:07:38,054
- Yeah, but it's yours to sell, right?

123
00:07:38,090 --> 00:07:39,079
- Yep.

124
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:41,753
- You know, I heard about all
the great parties she used to have up here.

125
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:43,318
You were never invited,
not even once?

126
00:07:43,362 --> 00:07:44,351
- Look at this.

127
00:07:44,397 --> 00:07:46,922
This is a genuine Iroquois vase
just sitting here.

128
00:07:46,966 --> 00:07:48,524
- Did you offend her in some way

129
00:07:48,568 --> 00:07:51,332
to insult her religious beliefs
or somethin'?

130
00:07:51,370 --> 00:07:53,634
'Oause, you know,
you're known for that.

131
00:07:53,673 --> 00:07:55,072
- The woman wasn't religious, Sully.

132
00:07:55,107 --> 00:07:56,768
- She went to church every Sunday, Bryan.

133
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:59,505
- Yeah, so did all those people in Salem
who burned the witches.

134
00:07:59,545 --> 00:08:00,910
- Yeah, right there, that comment?

135
00:08:00,947 --> 00:08:04,348
That's the kind of thing that might
offend someone that was human.

136
00:08:04,383 --> 00:08:05,645
- I wasn't offensive, Sully.

137
00:08:05,685 --> 00:08:06,743
I was sweet and thoughtful,

138
00:08:06,786 --> 00:08:08,845
and I was the lawyer in the family.

139
00:08:08,888 --> 00:08:12,289
Get you out of a parking ticket,
manslaughter, whatever you need.

140
00:08:12,325 --> 00:08:13,417
Solid mahogany.

141
00:08:13,459 --> 00:08:16,155
- Yeah, but, you know,
something still doesn't add up, you know?

142
00:08:16,195 --> 00:08:19,426
You got your classic mystery here.

143
00:08:19,465 --> 00:08:20,454
Don't you see that?

144
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:22,434
- Yeah, it's right up there
with crop circles.

145
00:08:22,468 --> 00:08:24,436
- Okay.
You know what?

146
00:08:24,470 --> 00:08:26,495
I don't care how high
your IQ test scores were.

147
00:08:26,539 --> 00:08:28,905
You lack common curiosity,
and that's a flaw.

148
00:08:28,941 --> 00:08:29,930
It is.

149
00:08:29,976 --> 00:08:31,102
And I've got it.

150
00:08:31,143 --> 00:08:32,474
You know,
I'm curious all day long.

151
00:08:32,512 --> 00:08:33,501
I'm like a two-year-old.

152
00:08:33,546 --> 00:08:35,070
- You want to hear my theory
on my aunt?

153
00:08:35,114 --> 00:08:37,548
- You have a theory?

154
00:08:37,583 --> 00:08:42,384
- I don't think she was the saint
that everybody thought she was.

155
00:08:42,421 --> 00:08:49,088
I think she was hiding something
about herself or about her past.

156
00:08:49,128 --> 00:08:51,028
And she feared being around
someone like me,

157
00:08:51,063 --> 00:08:54,089
someone who was smart
and shared her blood.

158
00:08:54,133 --> 00:08:58,035
I just might figure it out.

159
00:08:58,070 --> 00:08:59,765
That's a pretty juicy theory.

160
00:08:59,805 --> 00:09:01,966
It's right up your alley.

161
00:09:02,008 --> 00:09:03,066
What do you think, Sul?

162
00:09:03,109 --> 00:09:04,474
- [gasping]

163
00:09:04,510 --> 00:09:05,738
- Sully!
Sully!

164
00:09:05,778 --> 00:09:07,973
[crashing]

165
00:09:08,014 --> 00:09:09,072
Hey!

166
00:09:09,115 --> 00:09:10,104
Sully?

167
00:09:10,149 --> 00:09:11,707
Sully.

168
00:09:11,751 --> 00:09:12,740
Where's your juice?

169
00:09:12,785 --> 00:09:15,185
Where's your juice?

170
00:09:15,221 --> 00:09:16,813
Where's your ju... okay.

171
00:09:16,856 --> 00:09:18,084
I got it.

172
00:09:18,124 --> 00:09:19,182
All right, just hang on, pal.

173
00:09:19,225 --> 00:09:20,214
You're gonna be fine.

174
00:09:20,259 --> 00:09:21,590
Let's just get some juice in you.

175
00:09:21,627 --> 00:09:25,188
- There's something upstairs
in the closet

176
00:09:25,231 --> 00:09:27,426
behind the crucifix.

177
00:09:27,466 --> 00:09:29,434
- What?

178
00:09:29,468 --> 00:09:30,457
Oome on.

179
00:09:30,503 --> 00:09:32,300
Sip this.

180
00:09:32,338 --> 00:09:33,464
Sip it.

181
00:09:33,506 --> 00:09:35,303
Good, good.

182
00:09:35,341 --> 00:09:36,330
That better?

183
00:09:36,375 --> 00:09:38,275
- Yeah.
- Feelin' better?

184
00:09:38,311 --> 00:09:39,300
Is it working?
- Mm-hmm.

185
00:09:39,345 --> 00:09:40,334
- Good.

186
00:09:40,379 --> 00:09:41,471
You didn't eat today, did you?

187
00:09:41,514 --> 00:09:42,503
- No.

188
00:09:42,548 --> 00:09:43,537
- Well, God damn it, Sully.

189
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:45,073
You can't take those pills
and not eat.

190
00:09:45,117 --> 00:09:47,677
How long's it gonna take you
to learn that?

191
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:49,153
- Apparently a little while longer.

192
00:09:49,188 --> 00:09:51,622
- Yeah, have a little more.

193
00:09:51,657 --> 00:09:53,648
- Okay.
Yeah.

194
00:09:53,693 --> 00:09:55,820
Oh.

195
00:09:55,861 --> 00:09:57,795
- What was that you were
blabbing about?

196
00:09:57,830 --> 00:09:59,821
A closet upstairs with a crucifix?

197
00:09:59,865 --> 00:10:01,355
- Did I say something?

198
00:10:01,400 --> 00:10:02,799
Did I say something weird?

199
00:10:02,835 --> 00:10:04,803
- What's this?

200
00:10:04,837 --> 00:10:06,168
- I think it was on the desk.

201
00:10:06,205 --> 00:10:07,194
- All right, come on.

202
00:10:07,239 --> 00:10:09,400
You need food.

203
00:10:10,843 --> 00:10:11,969
Hey.

204
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:13,535
You and I need to have a little talk.

205
00:10:13,579 --> 00:10:15,046
- Man to man?

206
00:10:15,081 --> 00:10:16,639
- Man to man.

207
00:10:20,052 --> 00:10:23,579
Now, your mom and I told you
that my Aunt Marlene died, right?

208
00:10:23,623 --> 00:10:24,612
- Her heart got old.

209
00:10:24,657 --> 00:10:25,646
- Yeah.

210
00:10:25,691 --> 00:10:28,125
And I'm in charge
of selling her house.

211
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:30,128
She's got a lot of expensive
stuff over there,

212
00:10:30,162 --> 00:10:34,826
so I'm gonna have to go
and live there for a while,

213
00:10:34,867 --> 00:10:36,801
make sure nobody takes anything.

214
00:10:36,836 --> 00:10:38,599
- Okay.

215
00:10:38,638 --> 00:10:39,935
Oan I visit?

216
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:42,031
- Of course you can.

217
00:10:42,074 --> 00:10:43,063
Whenever you want.

218
00:10:43,109 --> 00:10:45,441
And you can call me too, okay?

219
00:10:45,478 --> 00:10:47,343
- Okay.

220
00:10:47,380 --> 00:10:50,144
- I got to go tell Mom.

221
00:10:50,182 --> 00:10:51,206
- Be careful.

222
00:10:51,250 --> 00:10:52,774
She's still mad from breakfast.

223
00:10:59,892 --> 00:11:03,953
- Hey.

224
00:11:03,996 --> 00:11:06,487
Look, my aunt's house is just
gonna sit there until we sell it.

225
00:11:06,532 --> 00:11:08,159
So I was thinking maybe I'd use it.

226
00:11:11,637 --> 00:11:14,071
You know, just for a few weeks
or so like we talked about.

227
00:11:14,106 --> 00:11:15,539
- Like we talked about?

228
00:11:15,574 --> 00:11:16,700
- Yes.

229
00:11:16,742 --> 00:11:17,902
Didn't we talk about this?

230
00:11:17,943 --> 00:11:20,070
Didn't we talk about how
some time apart

231
00:11:20,112 --> 00:11:21,602
might be exactly what we need
right now?

232
00:11:21,647 --> 00:11:24,047
Didn't we say that was something
we should seriously consider?

233
00:11:24,083 --> 00:11:25,243
- Yes, we said that.

234
00:11:25,284 --> 00:11:27,582
But one of us was bluffing.

235
00:11:27,620 --> 00:11:29,588
I guess we know now it wasn't you.

236
00:11:29,622 --> 00:11:33,854
- No.

237
00:11:33,893 --> 00:11:36,453
It wasn't me.

238
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:16,291
[sighs]

239
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:24,632
[garbled voices]

240
00:12:33,319 --> 00:12:34,684
- Hi, this is Marlene Deaver.

241
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:35,812
Please leave a message.

242
00:12:35,855 --> 00:12:39,484
Thank you.

243
00:12:39,525 --> 00:12:40,514
- It's Bryan Becket.

244
00:12:40,559 --> 00:12:42,151
Please leave a message.

245
00:12:42,194 --> 00:12:44,025
[loud thud and shaking glass]

246
00:12:44,063 --> 00:12:45,690
[glass shaking]

247
00:14:00,239 --> 00:14:03,697
[stairs creak]

248
00:14:03,742 --> 00:14:05,903
[wind whistling]

249
00:14:12,918 --> 00:14:15,910
[bed creaking]

250
00:14:18,657 --> 00:14:21,649
[people chatting]

251
00:14:24,330 --> 00:14:25,354
Mornin', Oarol.

252
00:14:25,397 --> 00:14:27,126
Hey, it's no rush,

253
00:14:27,166 --> 00:14:29,259
but I still need
the Benes motion to compel.

254
00:14:29,301 --> 00:14:31,394
Are you okay?

255
00:14:31,437 --> 00:14:34,600
- I'm fine.

256
00:14:35,941 --> 00:14:38,171
- Morning, Riley, Sarah.

257
00:14:40,246 --> 00:14:42,146
What is wrong with everyone today?

258
00:14:42,181 --> 00:14:43,705
Hey, could I talk to you
for a second?

259
00:14:43,749 --> 00:14:44,807
- Mm-hmm.

260
00:14:46,418 --> 00:14:48,909
- Please be seated.

261
00:14:48,954 --> 00:14:50,251
Are you and Robin separated?

262
00:14:50,289 --> 00:14:53,224
Now, I only know this because
Robin called Oeleste

263
00:14:53,259 --> 00:14:55,159
who called Karen,

264
00:14:55,194 --> 00:14:57,389
so it's gonna be on O-SPAN
in, like, five minutes.

265
00:14:57,429 --> 00:14:59,260
- That's between Robin and me.

266
00:14:59,298 --> 00:15:00,993
- And Oeleste and Karen.
